4d6.title: Contributing to Arbital
4d6.clickbait: Want to help Arbital become awesome?
4d6.text:
We want Arbital to have lots of awesome content that people can learn from, and we want it to be a pleasure to use for both readers and authors. For that, we need your help, whether that's as simple as letting us know when there's a bug or something that's poorly explained, or as in-depth as writing a full [1rt guide] to a topic.

### Join our slack

If you'd like to get involved, joining our [4ph Slack] is a great first step! Send your email to eric.bruylant@arbital.com and you'll be invited.

### Giving feedback on the site

If at any point you notice a bug, something you think could be improved about the site, or something you think is great, let us know! We want to understand how you interact with Arbital as a reader or editor, so we can make it work better for you. You can send feedback via an option in the quick menu (orange + button in the bottom right corner).

### Giving feedback on and editing pages

If you like something, give it a thumbs up! If you see anything you think could be improved (e.g. typos, [16t style issues], or things which could be explained better) you're encouraged to leave a comment on the page by highlighting the relevant text and using the + menu that appears. Or, if you have an idea about how to improve it yourself, propose an edit! Dive right in, you won't break anything :)

### Writing and improving individual pages

Writing both definition and explanation pages about specific subtopics is important to creating the network of knowledge that the rest of Arbital will be based on. The [home page](https://arbital.com) shows the most linked to pages which don't yet exist, but you are welcome to create a page for any math topic that readers would want to read about. [todo: Great examples of individual pages]

When creating pages, prioritize writing excellent [1kl summaries] for the preview popup. Put yourself in the mind of someone who wants a quick but accurate idea what the topic is about and check other summaries of the concept to confirm you're covering all the crucial points. Examples of pages with good summaries: [3nd], [3wn], [3g8], [3jy].

[todo: Shovel-ready pages, tags, wanted pages, etc.]

[todo: Quality assessment howto]

### Writing guides

If you've got [327 something to explain], creating complete guides we can [Arbital_featured feature] is extremely valuable. This is the most in-depth type of contribution, but it's proportionally rewarding. We'll be putting these in prominent places as a demonstration of how Arbital can help accelerate learning. For examples of these, see [1zq] and [3wj] (though note that both of these are still being polished).
